HOL-2: React Components

React components vs JavaScript functions

A component is a function (or class) that returns UI, described using JSX
A plain JS function returns any value; a component specifically returns renderable elements
Components can hold their own state and lifecycle; plain functions cannot
Components are invoked using JSX tags like <Home />, not function-call syntax
React treats components as reusable, composable building blocks of the UI

Types of components

Class components: ES6 classes that extend React.Component
Function components: plain JavaScript functions that return JSX
Function components are simpler and are now the preferred, modern approach
Class components support lifecycle methods natively; function components use Hooks for the same
Both types can accept props and render output

Class components

Defined using the class keyword and extending React.Component
Must implement a render() method that returns JSX
Can hold internal state using this.state
Access props via this.props
Commonly used before Hooks were introduced in React 16.8

Component constructor

The constructor is a special method called when a class component is created
Used to initialize state and bind event handler methods
Must call super(props) first to properly set up the component
Runs only once, when the component is first instantiated
Not required if the component has no state or bindings to set up

render() function

Every class component must define a render() method
It returns the JSX that describes what should appear on the screen
React calls render() whenever the component needs to update the UI
The returned JSX must have a single root element (or fragment)
It should be a pure function — no side effects, just return UI based on current props/state
